        "_account_id": 805,
        "name": "Neil Brown",
        "email": "neil@brown.name",
        "username": "neilbrown"
      },
      "date": "2023-08-02 03:53:19.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI cannot help wonder if there is a better way... we are constantly tracking a moving target here.\n\nI just tried to build with rpm-5.3.18-150300.59.127 which is the latest SP3 (source commit June 30th) and the ldiskfs patches don't apply.\n\nCould you at least include the precise kernel version in the commit message, rather than just \"latest\"?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "ad067eed0343bf5257e12e4be22ef9b452644e3d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 808,
        "name": "Shaun Tancheff",
        "email": "shaun.tancheff@hpe.com",
        "username": "stancheff"
      },
      "date": "2023-08-02 08:24:49.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> Patch Set 3:\n> \n> I cannot help wonder if there is a better way... we are constantly tracking a moving target here.\n> \n> I just tried to build with rpm-5.3.18-150300.59.127 which is the latest SP3 (source commit June 30th) and the ldiskfs patches don't apply.\n> \n> Could you at least include the precise kernel version in the commit message, rather than just \"latest\"?\n\n:( ... it was 5.3.18-150300.59.106-default ... I'll grab the latest as see if this can be improved",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "ad90210af2f63cf5b8ff9f482a670b34b93aebaa",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 805,
        "name": "Neil Brown",
        "email": "neil@brown.name",
        "username": "neilbrown"
      },
      "date": "2023-08-07 00:23:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI discovered that my build was failing because this patch creates a finer dependency on $LINUXRELEASE and they way I was building the SLE kernel that was just 5.3.18-default.\nI fixed my build and this patch builds properly now.\n\nLooking that what it actually does I see there is more than updating ext4-pdirop.patch.\nThe patch also drops:\n\nrhel8/ext4-ext-merge.patch\nrhel8/ext4-old_ea_inodes_handling_fix.patch\nrhel8/ext4-encdata.patch\n\nwas that deliberate?  If so it should be explained.\n(this is seen from\n  diff -u ldiskfs/kernel_patches/series/ldiskfs-5.3.18-sles15sp3{,-59}.series\n)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
